2 (vii) collecting and maintaining health information;
3 (viii) education and training of health professionals; or
4 (ix) other public health measures as allowed by law;
5 (f) protect the public from the introduction and spread of communicable disease or other
6 conditions of public health importance, including through actions to ensure the removal of filth or other
7 contaminants that might cause disease or adversely affect public health;
8 (g) supervise or make inspections for conditions of public health importance and issue written
9 orders for compliance or for correction, destruction, or removal of the conditions;
10 (h) bring and pursue actions and issue orders necessary to abate, restrain, or prosecute the
11 violation of public health laws, rules, and local regulations;
12 (i) identify to the department an administrative liaison for public health. The liaison must be the
13 local health officer in jurisdictions that employ a full-time local health officer. In jurisdictions that do not employ a
14 full-time local health officer, the liaison must be the highest ranking public health professional employed by the
15 jurisdiction.
16 (j) subject to the provisions of 50-2-130, propose for adoption by the local governing body
17 necessary regulations that are not less stringent than state standards for the control and disposal of sewage
18 from private and public buildings and facilities that are not regulated by Title 75, chapter 6, or Title 76, chapter
19 4. The regulations must:
20 (i) describe standards for granting variances from the minimum requirements that are identical to
21 standards promulgated by the department of environmental quality and must provide for appeal of variance
22 decisions to the department of environmental quality as required by 75-5-305;
23 (ii) prohibit the construction of a subsurface wastewater treatment system if the associated mixing
24 zone would encroach onto adjacent property, except as allowed in 76-4-104(7)(i); and.
25 (iii) If if the local board of health regulates or permits water well drilling, the regulations must
26 prohibit the drilling of a well if the well isolation zone, as defined in 76-4-102, encroaches onto adjacent private
27 property without the authorization of the private property owner.
